UPDATE courses SET
course_description = '<div class="richtext richtext__medium"> <h6>Nurses transform and make a positive impact on people’s lives.</h6><div class="lede">Prepare for a successful healthcare career with our comprehensive course designed for the diverse roles of nurses.</div><p>Your learning is delivered in a highly supported environment with dedicated nursing teaching staff and a maximum 1:12 staff-to-student ratio for practical and simulation experiences. We''re here to help you with whatever you need, when you need it, and ensure that your learning experience is personalised and focused, just like the care you''ll be providing as a registered nurse.</p><p>You''ll undertake a minimum of 800 hours of Professional Experience Placements across five different clinical and healthcare environments. We''ll prepare you to be solution-focused, compassionate, agile, and resilient, developing the clinical reasoning and practical skills required for your role as a registered nurse.</p><p id="reduced">If you need to study away from home, our <a href="https://www.utas.edu.au/study/scholarships-fees-and-costs/domestic-scholarships/support-to-study-scholarship-package" target="_blank">Relocation and Travel Support Allowance</a> helps cover accommodation and associated costs within Tasmania.</p><h6><strong>Graduate faster with our two-year accelerated study option</strong></h6><p>After your first year of study, you have the option based on your GPA, and placement availability, to undertake an accelerated plan to complete the entire degree in just two years. By utilising spring, summer, and winter study periods in year 2, you complete the same number of units in a shorter time, graduating sooner and allowing you to start your career faster.</p><p><strong>This is a quota course. To be considered for a first-round offer, submit your application by 5:00 pm on Tuesday, September 30, 2025 (also known as ‘on-time applications’). </strong></p><p><strong>Don’t worry if you miss this deadline—you can still apply! Applications will remain open until campus quotas are filled. Offers are based on the availability of remaining places at each of our campuses</strong></p> </div>',
    total_course_duration = 'Minimum 3 years, up to a maximum of 7 years.',
    offshore_tuition_fee = '129095',
    entry_requirements = '<div class="accordion--content"> <p>This is a quota course. To be considered for a <b>first-round offer</b>, submit your application by <b>5:00 pm on Tuesday, September 30, 2025</b> (also known as ‘on-time applications’). Don’t worry if you miss this deadline—you can still apply! We’ll consider you for subsequent offer rounds based on the availability of remaining places.</p> <p>All international students will need to meet the minimum English Language Requirements, University General Entry Requirements and any course specific requirements such as pre-requisite subjects, if applicable.</p> <p><b>English Language Requirements </b></p> <p>Standard 1.3 of the Australian Nursing and Midwifery Accreditation Council requires that students demonstrate English language proficiency. All applicants must provide either a written declaration that English is their primary language, or evidence that they have achieved the minimum English language test results (see details, below), as stipulated by the Nursing and Midwifery Board of Australia (NMBA) English language skills registration standard (2025).</p> <p>All applicants for whom English is not the primary language require one of:</p> <ul> <li>IELTS overall 7.0 (minimum score of 7.0 in each three components of listening, reading and speaking and a minimum score of 6.5 in writing), or</li> <li>Occupational English Test - OET (with a minimum score of B in each of the three components (listening, reading and speaking) and minimum score of C+ in writing, or</li> <li>TOEFL iBT with a minimum total score of 94 and the following minimum score in each section of the test: 24 for listening, 24 for reading, 24 for writing, and 23 for speaking, or</li> <li>Pearson Test of English - PTE Academic (with a minimum overall score of 66 and a minimum score of 66 in each of the four communicative skills (listening, reading and speaking) and minimum score of 56 in communication skill of writing.</li> </ul> <p>As the standard is set by the NMBA, please refer to their website for full details.</p> <p>For students who do not meet the English Language Requirement through citizenship, evidence of an approved English language test completed within the last 2 years must be provided. See the <a href="https://www.utas.edu.au/international/applying/entry-requirements/english-language-requirements">English Language Requirements</a> page for more information.</p> <p><b>General Entry Requirements</b></p> <p>For Hobart, Launceston and Burnie campuses, at least 90% of domestic places will be reserved for Tasmanian residents. Residency is based on residential address. </p> <p>Admission to undergraduate courses at the University of Tasmania requires the completion of qualifications equivalent to a 12th year of education in Australia.</p> <p>Please review the <a href="https://www.utas.edu.au/international/applying/entry-requirements/equivalent-undergraduate-entry-requirements-by-country">equivalent undergraduate entry requirements</a> to see the minimum requirement relevant to your country. The ATAR information for this course is located in the “For Domestic Students” section of the entry requirements on this page.</p> <p>Admission to the Bachelor of Nursing is highly competitive and that achieving the entry requirements does not guarantee an offer for this course. Applicants who meet the entry requirements are ranked and offers are made based on the number of places available.</p> <p>You can also meet the General Entry Requirement for this course with the following qualifications or prior studies:</p> <ul> <li>Completion of an equivalent AQF Diploma or higher</li> <li>Complete or incomplete (minimum 25 credit points) of previous tertiary study at Bachelor level or higher</li> </ul> <p>If you do not meet the minimum requirements, we offer the <a href="https://www.utas.edu.au/courses/acad/courses/x0f-foundation-studies-program-standard">Foundation Studies Program.</a></p> <p> </p> <p><em><b>Enrolled Nurse to Registered Nurse Pathway</b></em></p> <p>As this is a quota course, there are limited places at each campus. Offers for eligible Enrolled Nurses will be made in rounds, based on their time of application, until the quota has been filled. Remaining applicants will remain on a waitlist should a place open in that campus. </p> <p>To be eligible to undertake the Enrolled Nurse to Registered Nurse pathway, applicants <b>must </b>hold current registration as an Enrolled Nurse with Ahpra with no restrictions or conditions to practice, If an Enrolled Nurse opts to study a Bachelor of Nursing with the University of Tasmania and they have met the above requirements, they are eligible for 8 units of defined credit toward their study.</p> <p> </p> <p><b>Course Specific Requirements</b></p> <p><b>Safety In Practice Requirements</b></p> <p>This course includes compulsory Professional Experience Placements. You must meet the College of Health and Medicine''s <a href="https://www.utas.edu.au/health/professional-experience-placement/safety-in-practice-requirements">Safety in Practice Requirements</a> before census date of the first semester of your course. The safety in practice requirements are completed separately to the course admission application.</p> </div>',
    apply_form = 'https://apply.utas.edu.au'
WHERE cricos_course_code = '102253H';

