UPDATE courses SET
course_description = '<div class="richtext richtext__medium"> <div class="lede">Addiction and addictive behaviours manifest in various forms, from substance use involving drugs, medications, alcohol and nicotine to addiction in other areas of life, such as internet use, gambling, gaming, hoarding and many others. These behaviours can have devastating effects on the psychological and physical health of individuals, and on families, friends and communities.</div><p>​In Australia, the prevalence of mental health issues and disorders is significant, and there is a direct correlation between mental health and substance use. This underscores the urgent need for skilled health professionals who can provide evidence-informed assessment, care and support</p><p>In this fully online course you will work with both health and non-health professionals to improve your understanding of dependency and contribute to providing effective care and guidance to help those experiencing addiction.</p><p>Your studies will cover the principles underlying addiction and the mechanisms and interventions for substance use and withdrawal. You will consider the identification of co-occurring conditions, and the rationale for undertaking biopsychosocial clinical assessments for clients. You will also consider the array of treatments available in this area from pharmacotherapies to psychological interventions.</p><p>Throughout the course, you will learn about policy and strategies which direct service delivery and client management processes and gain an understanding of current legislative requirements in this area.</p><hr/><h4>Health partner scholarships</h4><p>To help you advance your career, generous scholarships are available to employees of our valued industry partners. <a href="https://www.utas.edu.au/study/partners/health" title="Health partner scholarships">Search for your employer</a>, speak to your workplace, or contact us on <a href="tel:138827">13 8827</a> to find out more.</p> </div>',
    total_course_duration = 'Minimum 1 Year, up to a maximum of 3 years.',
    offshore_tuition_fee = '',
    entry_requirements = '',
    apply_form = 'https://apply.utas.edu.au'
WHERE cricos_course_code = 'UNKNOWN';

UPDATE courses SET
course_description = '<div class="richtext richtext__medium"> <div class="lede">Addiction and addictive behaviours can take many forms and may have serious psychological and physical effects. Addiction is most commonly associated with drugs (both illicit and prescription), alcohol and nicotine. People can also become addicted to work, shopping, eating or dieting, computer and gaming use, alongside other dependent items.</div><p>In 2021, around 20% of Australians experienced a mental health disorder* and people with mental health conditions or high psychological distress are more likely to smoke and use illicit drugs or alcohol. The challenges they face take a severe toll on their quality of life, as well as those around them and the communities in which they live.</p><p>In this fully online course you will work with both health and non-health professionals to improve your understanding of dependency and contribute to providing effective care and guidance to help those experiencing overcome their struggle.</p><p>Your studies will cover the principals underlying substance use and withdrawal, identification of co-occurring conditions, and the rationale for undertaking bio-psychosocial clinical assessments for clients.</p><p>You will also learn about policy and strategies which direct appropriate client management processes, as well as gain an understanding of current legislative requirements.</p><p>In a self-directed capstone unit, you will tailor your studies towards a dependency related topic of your choice, gathering evidence and content to produce a professional portfolio to show your demonstrated knowledge relevant to the region, area, occupation, or sector where you’ll be utilising your skills.</p><hr/><h4>Health partner scholarships</h4><p>To help you advance your career, generous scholarships are available to employees of our valued industry partners. <a href="https://www.utas.edu.au/study/partners/health" title="Health partner scholarships">Search for your employer</a>, speak to your workplace, or contact us on <a href="tel:138827">13 8827</a> to find out more.</p><hr/><h6>Watch our webinar</h6><p>Our course coordinators provide information on our Graduate Certificate of Adddication Studies to help you discover where further study can take you.</p><p><a class="btn t-utas" href="https://youtu.be/N6r-_vpw1u4">Watch now</a></p><hr/> </div>',
