UPDATE courses SET
course_description = '<div class="richtext richtext__medium"> <div class="lede">The Graduate Certificate in Forestry has been developed to equip current industry professionals with the essential capabilities required to meet contemporary challenges. It fosters a new generation of forestry practitioners and leaders by offering a pathway for upskilling the workforce and preparing graduates for diverse roles in forest management. The course ensures the sector remains robust, adaptable, and appropriately skilled to address future challenges, particularly those posed by climate change.</div><p>The course is delivered through a collaboration between leading Australian universities in forestry research and education: the University of Tasmania, the Australian National University, University of Adelaide (formally from University of South Australia), the University of Melbourne, and the University of the Sunshine Coast.</p><p>Students will explore the changing ownership and management of forests in Australia over the past fifty years, the range of products and services forests provide, and the trade-offs involved in managing these. They will gain an understanding of carbon forestry, plantation management, and forest operations. They will gain insights into how forest management intersects with agriculture, peri-urban environments, and the construction and energy supply chains, all of which play a critical role in sustainability and decarbonisation efforts.</p><p>The course’s flexible delivery model, combining online learning with intensive field-based experiences, is designed to suit a working, mature, and regionally dispersed cohort. Through this innovative, multi-institutional collaboration, students will gain practical, region-specific forestry experience, positioning them to excel in both public and private sectors.</p><p>This graduate certificate not only responds to an urgent industry need but also empowers students to contribute meaningfully to sustainable forest management and policy development, both of which are increasingly vital to achieving Australia’s decarbonisation and sustainability goals.</p> </div>',
