course_description = '<div class="richtext richtext__medium"> <div class="lede">By understanding the issues facing our planet, you can help build a better future.</div><p>There is no better place to study natural environments and conservation than Tasmania. Our state is a living laboratory, with approximately 23% of Tasmania recognised as world heritage, and 42% as protected areas, accessible from our campus. Your studies will also connect you to the rich culture of the conservation movement in Tasmania.</p><p>Understanding the connections between nature and human society is vital for informing the management, protection, and use of the natural environment. You’ll learn to think critically and creatively across disciplines. As a graduate, you’ll fight to protect and heal our planet.</p><h6 id="duration">Online Study</h6><p>The Bachelor of Natural Environments Conservation can be studied predominantly online. Online students can choose to join us in the classroom via zoom for synchronous learning opportunities such as lectures and practical classes. Online students can also study in their own time.</p><p>However, the Bachelor of Natural Environments Conservation does have three units that have compulsory face-to-face activities. This means you’ll need to come to Tasmania to complete these units (normally, over a short-period of time, up to 10-days). These units are KGA213 which is studied at the end of first year, KGA331 which is studied at the end of second year and KGA318 which is studied at the end of third year. Students may also attend the optional camp or mandatory equivalent online activities in KGA327. For further information, please see the unit descriptions in the Course and Unit Handbook or consult the course co-ordinator.</p><h6 id="duration">Catalyst Program</h6><p>Want to combine your degree with overseas trips, summer research programs, scholarships and special events? Our Catalyst Program offers domestic high achieving school leavers all this and more.</p><p>All domestic students with an ATAR of 90 or greater, enrolled in a range of STEM courses will be awarded a $3,000 Catalyst Scholarship. Across the program students can access scholarships of up to $14,500 in value, and gain experience that will make you stand out in your chosen field. <a href="https://www.utas.edu.au/study/catalyst-program">Learn more about the Catalyst Program</a></p><h6>Combine the Bachelor of Natural Environments and Conservation with a Master of Protected Area Conservation</h6><p>The new Natural Environments and Conservation/Protected Area Conservation double degree allows you to graduate with an undergraduate and postgraduate degree full-time in just four-years (or part-time equivalent). <a href="https://www.utas.edu.au/study/undergraduate/natural-environments-and-conservation" target="_blank" title="Bachelor of Natural Environments and Conservation and Master of Protected Area Conservation">Read more about this study option and how to apply here</a>.</p><p>This degree can be combined to form a double degree. Study what you want, <a href="https://www.utas.edu.au/study/undergraduate/double-degrees">explore your options</a> and find out how you can accelerate your career.</p><hr/><h6>Watch our course information webinar</h6><p>Thinking of studying this course in 2025 and want to learn more? This webinar explores course structures, career opportunities, and the student experience to support your study journey.</p><p><a href="https://youtu.be/5hNChzERxAw" target="_blank" title="Watch our webinar">Watch now</a></p><h6><strong>Ready to explore your study options?</strong></h6><p>Book an online one-on-one appointment with our course coordinator to discuss any course-related questions and explore how the Bachelor of Natural Environments and Conservation can support your study and career goals.</p><p><a href="https://outlook.office365.com/owa/calendar/BachelorofNaturalEnvironmentsandConservationcourseadvice@UniversityTasmania.onmicrosoft.com/bookings/" target="_blank" title="Book now">Book now</a></p> </div>',
